We can see that bmi and disease progression share a positive correlation. Which was also evident in the scatter plot¶

Now that we have explored the data and the features used in the Univariate Regression Model, Let's proceed with the model construction process¶
Lets Split our dataset randomly with 75% in train dataset and the remaining 25% in the test set¶
In [ ]:
train_size = int(len(diabetes_df) * 0.75)
train = diabetes_df[:train_size]
test = diabetes_df[train_size:]
Now lets do a scatter plot for the training set and the test set to see if the propertions are random or not¶
In [ ]:
sns.scatterplot(x="bmi", y="target", data=train, color="blue", label='Training data')
sns.scatterplot(x="bmi", y="target", data=test, color="red", label='Testing data')
plt.title('BMI vs. Disease Progression')
plt.xlabel('Body Mass Index (BMI)')
plt.ylabel('Disease Progression')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
We can see here the data has been split randomly train is in blue and test is in red¶
Now lets start by training our model¶
In [ ]:
model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model.fit(X=train[["bmi"]], y=train["target"])

In [ ]:
sns.scatterplot(x="bmi", y="target", data=train, color="blue", label='Training data')

plt.title('BMI vs. Disease Progression (Training data)')
plt.xlabel('Body Mass Index (BMI)')
plt.ylabel('Disease Progression')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
In [ ]:
train_mse = mean_squared_error(train["target"], model.predict(train[["bmi"]]))
train_mae = mean_absolute_error(train["target"], model.predict(train[["bmi"]]))
print("Train set")
print(f"Mean squared error: {train_mse}")
print(f"Mean absolute error: {train_mae}")

Train set
Mean squared error: 3955.532108237149
Mean absolute error: 52.100347415906704
Now that we have calculated the MAE and MSE for the train set and plotted the regression line lets do the same for the test set¶
In [ ]:
test_mse = mean_squared_error(test["target"], model.predict(test[["bmi"]]))
test_mae = mean_absolute_error(test["target"], model.predict(test[["bmi"]]))
print("Test set")
print(f"Mean squared error: {test_mse}")
print(f"Mean absolute error: {test_mae}")

Test set
Mean squared error: 3698.612229796081

sns.scatterplot(x="bmi", y="target", data=test, color="red", label='Testing data')

plt.title('BMI vs. Disease Progression (Testing data)')
plt.xlabel('Body Mass Index (BMI)')
plt.ylabel('Disease Progression')

As evident from the performance of the model on both the train and the test set there is room for improvement as right now it is a coin flip as the error rates are relatively high about 50%¶
Moreover, The MAE and the MSE suggest that the model does well against the unpredictably of the dataset but still requires further parameter tuning and validation¶
The model here is not overfitting as the model does reasonably well gor the test data as the error value is lower than that of the train set. While the model does showcase that predictions can be made the error rate is still 50% so refining the model and cross validating might be necessary here.¶

To conclude the model provvides us a peek at the relationship between BMI and Disease progression. The model is not overfitting the data and has the slope value at 151.49 with coefficient at 941.47. The MSE and MAE values are 3995, 52.10 for the train dataset and 3698.61, 50.94 for the test dataset respectively. Hinting at a need of further tuning and training.¶
